I'll modify the following file: [38;5;141mchapter07.11-claim-denial-prediction.md[0m[38;5;244m (using tool: write)[0m
Purpose: Resolve finding L135 (R-1): Add gold-carding laws and CMS prior-auth reform paragraph to Honest Take

[49m[38;5;10m+      137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **State gold-carding laws and CMS prior-auth reform are reshaping the feature landscape.** Several states (Texas HB 3459, Louisiana, West Virginia, and others) have enacted "gold-carding" laws that exempt providers with high prior-authorization approval rates from PA requirements for specific payer-service pairs. If a provider maintains a 90%+ approval rate for a given procedure with a given payer over a lookback period, the payer must waive PA for that combination. Your model needs to know about these exemptions: if a provider-procedure-payer triple is gold-carded, the PA-related features should be suppressed (flagging "PA required but missing" for a gold-carded provider is a false alarm that erodes trust). Maintain a gold-card registry as a feature store lookup and update it as payers publish their exempt provider lists quarterly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m On the federal side, CMS finalized rule CMS-0057-F (effective January 2026) mandating that payers expose PA status, decisions, and requirements through standardized FHIR APIs (specifically the Da Vinci Prior Authorization Support Implementation Guide). This changes your feature engineering significantly: instead of inferring PA requirements from historical denial patterns, you can query the payer's FHIR endpoint directly for whether PA is required, what documentation is needed, and whether an existing PA is still active. Models built today on inferred PA features should plan for a transition to API-sourced PA features as payers implement the mandate. The FHIR API will also expose faster determination timelines (72 hours for urgent, 7 days for standard under the new rule), which compresses your intervention window for pre-visit predictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 141[0m:[39m[49m **Be careful with "route to alternative pathway" recommendations.** The model predicts financial outcomes (will the payer pay?), not clinical appropriateness (is this the right treatment?). If the clinically appropriate procedure has a high predicted denial rate, the right answer is to strengthen the PA submission, not to change the treatment plan. Clinical decisions must remain independent of denial predictions. The model's job is to reduce administrative friction for clinically appropriate care, not to optimize treatment selection for financial outcomes. Make this boundary explicit in your operational policies and training materials.
[0m[K
